-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - Sept 2
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Mon Sep 01, 2014 10:25PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, Sept 2 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Tuesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  - The Hong Kong Economic Journal has scrapped political activist Edward Chin Chi-kin's weekly column, leading the hedge fund manager to blast the move as a "political decision". (http://bit.ly/1r7X96i) - Top Communist Party leader Liu Yunshan, a member of the Politburo Standing Committee and head of the party secretariat, said that severe corruption and a "problematic" political scene had prompted a reshuffle in coal-rich Shanxi province. (http://bit.ly/1tpqg7C) - China Construction Bank <601939.SS> executives acknowledged that senior staff members at mainland state banks could face pay cuts in line with recent government reforms but pushed back against reports that general staff salaries would be slashed. (http://bit.ly/1qk8hNr)  THE STANDARD - Sino Land <0083.HK> and Chinese Estates <0127.HK> have won the mega Kwun Tong redevelopment project of the Urban Renewal Authority on its tender. The authority did not disclose the tendered price, but the winning bid was rumored to be below HK$7 billion ($903.21 million). (http://bit.ly/1nQzfrf) - Five firms will open their retail books this month to raise nearly HK$10 billion ($1.29 billion). China's largest car rental company CAR, formerly called China Auto Rental, plans to take orders from investors on Friday for HK$3.9 billion, while local contractor New Concepts Holdings is targeting HK$100 million. (http://bit.ly/1tprNub) - Huiyuan Juice Group <1886.HK> is banking on the international market, including Hong Kong, to boost sales after its disappointing first-half results. It also said chief executive Daniel Saw was leaving, and to be succeeded by vice president Yu Hongli effective next month. (http://bit.ly/1qwz4Vo)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  - The number of visitors from the mainland to Hong Kong increased 12.8 percent year on year in July at 4.26 million compared to a 7.8 percent rise in June, according to data from Hong Kong Toursim Board.  HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  - Huadian Power International Corp Ltd <1071.HK> <600027.SS> aims to expand its power generating capacity through building new facilities and acquisitions, while the company will also consider acquiring assets from its parent although no timetable has yet been set, according to vice chairman Chen Jianhua.MING PAO DAILY NEWS  - Massive class boycotts against Beijing's framework on Hong Kong elections will be launched in mid-September involving 11 higher educational institutions, said Federation of Students' secretary-general Alex Chow Yong-kang.